Principal components analysis

Gerko Vink

Statistical Programming in R

Recap

So far, we mostly investigated (bivariate) relations between observed data points.

This lecture we are considering multivariate relations and patterns.

We focus on Principal Components Analysis (PCA)

Principal Components Analysis

What is it

All the techniques we discussed so far are based on hypotheses testing (t-test, F-test, chi-square test). Also, the techniques require observed variables (DV and IVs).

However, sometimes we have a large number of observed variables, and we think that some of them measure an underlying dimension (e.g., intelligence, attitude towards drugs, extraversion, etc.).

The underlying dimensions are not observed: these are latent variables (also called factors or constructs).

Why factor analysis (and PCA)

Many theoretical constructs cannot be observed directly: We say such constructs are latent.

We try to infer their existence from the relations (correlations) between the observed variables.

\[ \rho_{X,Y} = \frac{\text{cov}(X,Y)}{\sigma_X\sigma_Y} = \frac{E[(X - \mu_{X})(Y-\mu_{Y})]}{\sigma_X\sigma_Y}\]

Because we try to understand the relations between the observed variables using a smaller number of latent variables, factor analysis is a form of data reduction

PCA = data transformation

Originally, PCA is a form of data transformation (not data reduction).

The first principal component is a linear combination of the observed variables, which explains most of the total observed variance.

Then second principal component is a linear combination of the observed variables, which explains most of the variance that was not accounted for by the first component.

This is continued until we have as many components as observed variables: no data reduction but data transformation

Visual example

Suppose we have two observed variables. Hence, there are two principal components, which describe all observed variance.

The solid red line represents the first principal component: it is a linear combination of the two original variables for which the explained variance is maximal.

The second principal component (dotted blue line) must be perpendicular to the first, to explain variance unaccounted for by the first principal component

Eigenvalues

Total variance in items:

  • Per item the variance is 1
  • The total variance = number of items = \(k\)

Eigenvalue (\(\lambda\)) of a component is the variance explained in all items by the component.

\[\lambda = \sum^{k}_{g=1} = a^2_{gj}\]

  • \(k\) is the number of items
  • \(a^2_{gj}\) = factorloading of item \(g\) on factor (component) \(j\)

A component with an eigenvalue \(\lambda > 1\) explains more variance than a single item (hence datareduction).

Communalities and Loadings

A communality is the proportion of jointly explained variance by all factors/components in one item (variable).

  • Uniqueness is the proportion of not-explained variance in one item (1 – communality)

Component loadings are the regression coefficients when regressing the observations on the components.

  • Loadings are equal to the correlations between the observations and the components.

require(lattice) 
colr <- c("red", "blue") 
pchr <- c(3,4,0,8,2,10,1) 
ss <- expand.grid(site=1:7, sex=1:2)           # Site varies fastest 
parset <- with(ss, simpleTheme(pch=pchr[site], col=colr[sex])) 
sitenames <- c("Cambarville","Bellbird","Whian Whian", "Byrangery", 
               "Conondale ","Allyn River", "Bulburin") 
## Add column sexsite to possum; will be used again below 
possum$sexsite <- paste(possum$sex, possum$site, sep="-") 
splom(possum[, c(9:11)], groups = possum$sexsite,  
      col = colr[ss$sex], par.settings=parset, 
      varnames=c("tail\nlength","foot\nlength","ear conch\nlength"), 
      key = list(text=list(sitenames), points=list(pch=pchr), columns=3))

These eigenvalues are completely different! (the first EV was 46.24)

This is because FactoMineR’s function PCA() scales the variables by default.

Factor loadings

Loadings are not given by FactoMineR. But you can calculate them by dividing the principal coordinates (factor scores - $var$coord) of a dimension by the square root of that dimensions’ eigenvalue.

sweep(pca2$var$coord,2,sqrt(pca2$eig[1:ncol(pca2$var$coord),1]),FUN="/")
